n, Hampshire County, Massachusetts","notes":"Per EH 1909 #529: 'He was a physician and also a trader at West Hampton, Mass.' — supplementing physician income with a trading operation, common pattern for rural New England doctors of the period."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Lived to ninety-four as Westhampton physician","body":"Born Northampton MA 1766; died Westhampton MA February 27, 1861 at age ninety-four — extraordinary longevity spanning the early Republic through the Civil War's outbreak. Practiced medicine in Westhampton MA and also operated as a trader; both occupations supported a large family of seven children with first wife Anna Thompson before her 1810 death."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Lost wife at forty-two, remarried after two years","body":"First wife Anna Thompson died Westhampton April 2, 1810 at age forty-two — leaving him with seven children ranging from twenty-four-year-old Henry down to eight-year-old Edward. William remarried 1812 to Rhoda Phelps, widow of Ensign Hartland of Hartland Connecticut. No documented children from the second marriage; Rhoda predeceased William by fourteen years."}],"former_ids":[],"slug":"william-hooker-1766"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}